# Flutter Clean Architecture with SOLID Principles & Bloc State Management

## Project Architecture Overview
This project follows Clean Architecture principles with clear separation of concerns across three main layers:
- **Domain Layer**: Business logic, entities, and repository interfaces
- **Data Layer**: Repository implementations, data sources, and models
- **Presentation Layer**: UI components, Bloc/Cubit state management

## Core Principles

### SOLID Principles Enforcement

#### Single Responsibility Principle (SRP)
- Each class should have only one reason to change
- Separate concerns: UI logic in widgets, business logic in use cases, data logic in repositories
- Use cases should handle only one specific business operation
- Blocs/Cubits should manage state for a single feature or screen

#### Open/Closed Principle (OCP)
- Use abstract classes and interfaces for extensibility
- Repository pattern with interfaces in domain layer, implementations in data layer
- Use case pattern with abstract UseCase base class
- Extend functionality through inheritance, not modification

#### Liskov Substitution Principle (LSP)
- Implementations should be substitutable for their interfaces
- Repository implementations must fully satisfy their domain contracts
- State classes should properly extend their base abstract states

#### Interface Segregation Principle (ISP)
- Keep interfaces focused and minimal
- Separate repository interfaces by feature (AuthRepository, MovieRepository, etc.)
- Use specific parameter objects instead of large parameter lists

#### Dependency Inversion Principle (DIP)
- High-level modules should not depend on low-level modules
- Use dependency injection (GetIt service locator)
- Domain layer should not depend on data or presentation layers
- Presentation layer depends on domain abstractions, not implementations

## Project Structure Rules

### Root Directory Structure
```
lib/
├── main.dart                 # App entry point with BlocProvider setup
├── service_locator.dart      # Dependency injection configuration
├── core/                     # Shared utilities and configurations
├── domain/                   # Business logic layer
├── data/                     # Data access layer
├── presentation/             # UI layer with Bloc state management
└── common/                   # Shared components and utilities
```

### Core Layer (`lib/core/`)
- **Purpose**: Shared utilities, configurations, and base classes
- **Structure**:
  ```
  core/
  ├── configs/
  │   ├── theme/              # App theming
  │   └── assets/             # Asset management
  ├── constants/              # App-wide constants
  ├── network/                # HTTP client configuration
  ├── usecase/                # Base UseCase abstract class
  ├── entity/                 # Base entity classes
  └── models/                 # Base model classes
  ```
- **Rules**:
  - Keep core utilities framework-agnostic
  - No business logic in core layer
  - Use abstract classes for extensible base functionality

### Domain Layer (`lib/domain/`)
- **Purpose**: Business logic, entities, and repository contracts
- **Structure**:
  ```
  domain/
  ├── auth/
  │   ├── entities/           # Business entities (pure Dart classes)
  │   ├── repositories/       # Repository interfaces
  │   └── usecases/          # Business use cases
  ├── movie/
  └── tv/
  ```
- **Rules**:
  - No external dependencies (no Flutter, HTTP, etc.)
  - Entities should be pure Dart classes with business logic
  - Repository interfaces define contracts, no implementations
  - Use cases should extend base UseCase class
  - Use Either<String, T> for error handling with dartz package
  - Each use case should have a single responsibility

### Data Layer (`lib/data/`)
- **Purpose**: Data access, repository implementations, and external service integration
- **Structure**:
  ```
  data/
  ├── auth/
  │   ├── models/            # Data transfer objects
  │   ├── sources/           # API services and local storage
  │   └── repositories/      # Repository implementations
  ├── movie/
  └── tv/
  ```
- **Rules**:
  - Models should extend domain entities or provide conversion methods
  - Repository implementations should implement domain repository interfaces
  - API services should be registered as singletons in service locator
  - Use Dio for HTTP requests with proper error handling
  - Separate remote and local data sources

### Presentation Layer (`lib/presentation/`)
- **Purpose**: UI components and state management with Bloc pattern
- **Structure**:
  ```
  presentation/
  ├── auth/
  │   ├── pages/             # Screen widgets
  │   ├── widgets/           # Feature-specific reusable widgets
  │   └── bloc/              # Bloc/Cubit state management
  ├── home/
  ├── search/
  ├── splash/
  └── watch/
  ```
- **Rules**:
  - Each feature should have its own folder
  - Use Bloc/Cubit for state management, not StatefulWidget for complex state
  - Pages should be stateless and delegate to Bloc/Cubit
  - Separate state classes for different states (Loading, Loaded, Error)
  - Use BlocBuilder, BlocListener, and BlocConsumer appropriately

## State Management with Bloc Pattern

### Bloc/Cubit Implementation
- Use Cubit for simple state management, Bloc for complex event handling
- Follow naming convention: `FeatureCubit`, `FeatureState`
- Inject use cases through service locator
- Handle loading, success, and error states explicitly

### State Classes
```dart
abstract class FeatureState {}

class FeatureLoading extends FeatureState {}

class FeatureLoaded extends FeatureState {
  final DataType data;
  FeatureLoaded({required this.data});
}

class FeatureError extends FeatureState {
  final String message;
  FeatureError({required this.message});
}
```

### Cubit Implementation Pattern
```dart
class FeatureCubit extends Cubit<FeatureState> {
  FeatureCubit() : super(FeatureLoading());

  void performAction() async {
    emit(FeatureLoading());
    final result = await sl<UseCase>().call();
    result.fold(
      (error) => emit(FeatureError(message: error)),
      (data) => emit(FeatureLoaded(data: data)),
    );
  }
}
```

## Dependency Injection Rules

### Service Locator Setup
- Register all dependencies in `service_locator.dart`
- Use singleton registration for stateless services
- Register in order: Network → Services → Repositories → Use Cases
- Use `sl<Type>()` for dependency resolution

### Registration Pattern
```dart
void setupServiceLocator() {
  // Network
  sl.registerSingleton<DioClient>(DioClient());
  
  // Services
  sl.registerSingleton<AuthService>(AuthApiServiceImpl());
  
  // Repositories
  sl.registerSingleton<AuthRepository>(AuthRepositoryImpl());
  
  // Use Cases
  sl.registerSingleton<SignupUseCase>(SignupUseCase());
}
```

## Code Quality and Best Practices

### Naming Conventions
- Use descriptive names that reflect business domain
- Classes: PascalCase (`UserRepository`, `SigninUseCase`)
- Files: snake_case (`user_repository.dart`, `signin_usecase.dart`)
- Folders: lowercase (`auth`, `movie`, `tv`)

### Error Handling
- Use Either<String, T> for use case returns
- Provide meaningful error messages
- Handle network errors, parsing errors, and business logic errors separately
- Use try-catch blocks in repository implementations

### Testing Structure
- Mirror lib structure in test folder
- Unit tests for use cases and repositories
- Widget tests for UI components
- Integration tests for complete user flows

### Code Organization Rules
1. **Import Order**: Dart core → Flutter → Third-party → Local imports
2. **File Structure**: Imports → Constants → Class definition → Methods
3. **Method Organization**: Public methods first, private methods last
4. **Documentation**: Use /// for public APIs, // for implementation details

## Feature Development Workflow

### Adding a New Feature
1. Create domain entities and repository interface
2. Implement use cases extending base UseCase
3. Create data models and repository implementation
4. Register dependencies in service locator
5. Implement Bloc/Cubit for state management
6. Create UI pages and widgets
7. Add to main app navigation

### Modifying Existing Features
1. Check if changes affect domain contracts
2. Update use cases if business logic changes
3. Modify repository implementations for data changes
4. Update Bloc/Cubit state management if needed
5. Adjust UI components as required

## Performance and Optimization

### State Management Optimization
- Use BlocBuilder only for UI that needs to rebuild
- Use BlocListener for side effects (navigation, snackbars)
- Implement proper equals/hashCode for state classes
- Avoid rebuilding entire widget trees

### Memory Management
- Dispose controllers and subscriptions properly
- Use const constructors where possible
- Optimize image loading and caching
- Implement proper list view recycling for large datasets

## Security Best Practices
- Store sensitive data in secure storage (not SharedPreferences)
- Validate all user inputs
- Implement proper authentication token management
- Use HTTPS for all network requests
- Sanitize data before display

## This rule ensures:
- Clean separation of concerns following Clean Architecture
- SOLID principles enforcement across all layers  
- Consistent Bloc/Cubit state management patterns
- Proper dependency injection and inversion of control
- Scalable project structure that grows with the application
- Type safety and error handling best practices
- Performance optimization through proper state management